THE Equity Bank Group is set to facilitate creation of 50 million jobs in East Africa in the next five years subjected to loan issuance. The group, operating in seven East African Countries member states, said the job creation will come after offering 13tri/- in loans to the area it operates in the region—including Tanzania. The group with headquarters in Kenya with subsidiaries in Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi, South Sudan and now DR-Congo said sets to provide loans to some 5 million people in the region. The Ministry of Finance and Planning, Deputy Permanent Secretary, Mr Lawrence Mafuru said in Dodoma on Wednesday that the bank would direct loans mainly to agriculture—especially irrigation and value addition, industry and SMEs. The deputy PS said the area the Group is focusing was in line with the government ambition to transform agricultural sector centring on irrigation and value addition to cut post-harvest losses. Mr Mafuru was speaking after meeting with the Group delegation that visited the ministry in Dodoma. The delegation was led by the Group Chief Planning Officer Mr Brent Malay. The Group, one of the largest lenders in the region, wants to use its financial muscles to create jobs while at the same time enable industries in the region to access industrial raw materials locally. Mr Malay said the Group wants to work with the government to boost job creation and economic growth through loans. The Equity Bank Tanzania Managing Director, Ms Isabela Maganga, said that the lender said the 13tril/- fund through loans geared at   increase investment in the country to stimulate production in priority areas.